{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539267","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539267"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:39:13+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:39:13+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16503"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16503","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16503"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.28,0.12,0.1,0.41]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9194"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102025"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9194","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9194"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16503"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84475"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21808"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21810"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35493"},{"type":"contributions","id":"48286"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/102025"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a five-month history of epigastric pain, loose, foul-smelling stools, and 6kg of weight loss. He has a history of heavy alcohol consumption with multiple previous episodes of acute pancreatitis and continues to drink approximately 6 standards daily. He takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears thin with a BMI of 19 kg/m2. His pulse rate is 82/min, blood pressure 118/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 16/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. His abdomen is soft with mild epigastric tenderness. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA computed tomography scan shows pancreatic calcifications, dilated pancreatic duct, and parenchymal atrophy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following additional investigations is indicated?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Serum amylase","Faecal elastase","Gastroscopy and colonoscopy","Endoscopic ultrasound","Serum cancer antigen 19-9"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has imaging findings diagnostic of chronic pancreatitis. Given his symptoms of steatorrhoea and weight loss, the next step is to assess for pancreatic exocrine insufficiency. \u003Cstrong\u003EFaecal elastase\u003C/strong\u003E is the preferred test for this purpose as it is non-invasive, not affected by pancreatic enzyme supplementation, and has good sensitivity and specificity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum amylase\u003C/strong\u003E would not be helpful as it is typically normal in chronic pancreatitis and is only elevated during acute exacerbations. Furthermore, it does not provide information about pancreatic function.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastroscopy and colonoscopy\u003C/strong\u003E would not be the first-line investigation as they do not directly visualise the pancreas. While they may be useful to exclude other gastrointestinal disease, the history strongly suggests pancreatic pathology. Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography would provide detailed imaging of the pancreatic ducts but is not necessary at this stage as CT has already confirmed the diagnosis of chronic pancreatitis. MRCP would be considered if there was concern about cholangiocarcinoma or if endoscopic or surgical intervention was being planned.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEndoscopic ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E can detect early changes of chronic pancreatitis but is not necessary when CT findings are diagnostic. It would be considered if the diagnosis was uncertain or if tissue sampling was required.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum cancer antigen 19-9\u003C/strong\u003E is a tumour marker that can be elevated in pancreatic cancer. While chronic pancreatitis patients have an increased risk of pancreatic cancer, there are no specific features in this case to suggest malignancy warranting tumour marker testing.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter confirming pancreatic exocrine insufficiency, other important investigations would include HbA1c to screen for type 3c diabetes, vitamin D levels, and other nutritional parameters given the risk of malabsorption. Management typically includes pancreatic enzyme replacement therapy, nutritional support, and ongoing monitoring for complications.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Chronic pancreatitis diagnosis requires both structural (imaging) and functional assessment of the pancreas.","Faecal elastase is the preferred test for diagnosing pancreatic exocrine insufficiency.","Other complications of chronic pancreatitis include chronic pain, endocrine insufficiency and malnutrition"],"references":["Chronic pancreatitis: Negotiating the complexities of diagnosis and management. Australian Journal for General Practitioners. 2015 Sep 21;44:718\u201322. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2015/october/chronic-pancreatitis-negotiating-the-complexities","Gardner TB, Adler DG, Forsmark CE, Sauer BG, Taylor JR, Whitcomb DC. ACG Clinical Guideline: Chronic Pancreatitis. Official journal of the American College of Gastroenterology | ACG [Internet]. 2020;115(3). Available from: https://journals.lww.com/ajg/fulltext/2020/03000/acg_clinical_guideline__chronic_pancreatitis.9.aspx"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84475"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16503"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84475","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84475"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-06T15:08:19+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-06T15:09:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9194"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"102025"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}